# HTML Content Extraction Expression Documentation

## Overview
This expression provides a robust solution for extracting and cleaning readable content from HTML markup. It systematically removes HTML structure while preserving meaningful text content, making it ideal for content extraction, search indexing, or text analysis purposes.

## Expression Structure
```javascript
{{
  (function(html) {
    // Remove DOCTYPE, comments, and processing instructions
    html = html.replace(/<!DOCTYPE[^>]*>|<!--[\s\S]*?-->|<\?[\s\S]*?\?>/g, '');

    // Remove script, style, svg, and other non-content tags
    html = html.replace(/<(script|style|svg|canvas|noscript|iframe|video|audio|object|embed)[\s\S]*?<\/\1>/gi, '');

    // Replace common entities
    html = html.replace(/&nbsp;/g, ' ').replace(/&amp;/g, '&').replace(/&lt;/g, '<').replace(/&gt;/g, '>');

    // Remove all remaining tags, but keep their content
    html = html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, ' ');

    // Collapse whitespace and trim
    html = html.replace(/\s+/g, ' ').trim();

    // Remove any leftover Unicode spaces and zero-width characters
    html = html.replace(/[\u200B-\u200D\uFEFF]/g, '');

    return html;
  })(input)
}}
```

## Process Breakdown

### 1. Metadata and Structure Removal
```javascript
html.replace(/<!DOCTYPE[^>]*>|<!--[\s\S]*?-->|<\?[\s\S]*?\?>/g, '');
```
- Removes DOCTYPE declarations
- Eliminates HTML comments
- Removes XML processing instructions
- Pattern explanation:
  - `<!DOCTYPE[^>]*>`: Matches DOCTYPE declarations
  - `<!--[\s\S]*?-->`: Matches HTML comments
  - `<\?[\s\S]*?\?>`: Matches processing instructions

### 2. Non-Content Element Removal
```javascript
html.replace(/<(script|style|svg|canvas|noscript|iframe|video|audio|object|embed)[\s\S]*?<\/\1>/gi, '');
```
- Removes elements that typically don't contain readable content
- Targeted elements:
  - `script`: JavaScript code
  - `style`: CSS styling
  - `svg`: Vector graphics
  - `canvas`: Drawing elements
  - `noscript`: Fallback content
  - `iframe`: Embedded frames
  - `video/audio`: Media elements
  - `object/embed`: External content
- The `\1` backreference ensures matching end tags

### 3. Entity Conversion
```javascript
html.replace(/&nbsp;/g, ' ').replace(/&amp;/g, '&').replace(/&lt;/g, '<').replace(/&gt;/g, '>');
```
- Converts common HTML entities to their character equivalents
- Transformations:
  - `&nbsp;`  space character
  - `&amp;`  &
  - `&lt;`  <
  - `&gt;`  >

### 4. Generic Tag Removal
```javascript
html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, ' ');
```
- Removes all remaining HTML tags
- Preserves the content between tags
- Replaces tags with spaces to prevent word joining

### 5. Whitespace Normalization
```javascript
html.replace(/\s+/g, ' ').trim();
```
- Collapses multiple whitespace characters into single spaces
- Removes leading and trailing whitespace
- Ensures consistent spacing in the output

### 6. Unicode Cleanup
```javascript
html.replace(/[\u200B-\u200D\uFEFF]/g, '');
```
- Removes problematic Unicode characters:
  - U+200B: Zero-width space
  - U+200C: Zero-width non-joiner
  - U+200D: Zero-width joiner
  - U+FEFF: Zero-width no-break space (BOM)

## Usage Considerations

### Best Practices
1. Input Validation: Ensure input is a string containing HTML
2. Error Handling: Wrap in try-catch when used in production
3. Performance: Consider input size limitations for large HTML documents

### Limitations
- Does not handle all HTML entities (focuses on common ones)
- May not preserve some text formatting nuances
- Could require adjustment for specific content structures

### Use Cases
- Content extraction for search indexing
- Text analysis and processing
- HTML to plain text conversion
- Content summarization
- Data cleaning pipelines

## Integration Examples

### Basic Usage
```javascript
const plainText = (function(html) {
    // ... [expression code] ...
})('<p>Hello, <strong>world</strong>!</p>');
// Result: "Hello, world!"
```

### With Error Handling
```javascript
try {
